1 Oppressed with wonder, to my guide
2 I turned me, like a little child who runs
3 always to where he most confides;

10 How would the singing have transformed you,
11 and I laughing, now you can think,
12 since the cry has moved you so much;

19 But turn yourself now toward others;
20 for you will see many illustrious spirits,
21 if you turn your gaze as I tell you.

25 I stood like one who represses in himself
26 the point of desire, and does not dare
27 to ask, so much does he fear excess;

37 That mountain on whose slope Cassino lies
38 was once frequented on its summit
39 by people who were deceived and ill-disposed;

40 and I am the one who first brought there
41 the name of him who brought to earth
42 the truth that so uplifts us;

67 because it is not in a place and does not move;
68 and our ladder reaches up to it,
69 from where it thus vanishes from your sight.

79 But grave usury is not taken
80 against the pleasure of God as much as that gain
81 which makes the hearts of monks so foolish;

82 because however much the Church may watch over it, everything
83 belongs to the people who ask for God's sake;
84 not to relatives or to anything else more vile.

88 Peter began without gold and without silver,
89 and I with prayer and with fasting,
90 and Francis his order in humility;

97 Thus he spoke to me, and then he gathered himself
98 to his company, and the company drew together;
99 then, like a whirlwind, it all spun upwards.

100 The sweet lady urged me on behind them
101 with a single gesture up that stairway,
102 so her power overcame my nature;

115 with you was born and with you was hidden
116 he who is the father of all mortal life,
117 when I first felt the Tuscan air;

124 "You are so close to the ultimate salvation,"
125 Beatrice began, "that you must
126 have your eyes clear and sharp;

127 and therefore, before you ascend further,
128 look down and see how much of the world
129 I have already made to be beneath your feet;

133 With my gaze I returned through all
134 the seven spheres, and I saw this globe
135 such that I smiled at its vile appearance;

145 Then the temperament of Jove appeared to me
146 between the father and the son; and then it was clear to me
147 the variation that they make of their places;

151 The threshing-floor that makes us so fierce,
152 as I turned with the eternal Twins,
153 appeared to me in its entirety from the hills to the mouths of the rivers;
